  <!-- 01 · DIAGRAM -->
  <section class="diagram-section" id="diagram">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="head">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow"><span class="num">No. 01</span><span class="rule-mini"></span>The relationship</div>
          <h2>Four parties. <em>One</em> chain of accountability.</h2>
        </div>
        <p>An HOA is a corporation owned by its homeowners. The board, elected by those owners, governs the corporation. The management company executes the board&rsquo;s direction. Vendors do the work the manager dispatches. Read the arrows in either direction &mdash; that&rsquo;s the system.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="diagram-frame">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 880 520" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" role="img" aria-label="Diagram of the HOA management relationship">
          <defs>
            <marker id="arrow-navy" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="9" refY="5" markerWidth="7" markerHeight="7" orient="auto">
              <path d="M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z" fill="#18335E"/>
            </marker>
            <marker id="arrow-green" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="9" refY="5" markerWidth="7" markerHeight="7" orient="auto">
              <path d="M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z" fill="#7AB31F"/>
            </marker>
            <marker id="arrow-steel" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="9" refY="5" markerWidth="7" markerHeight="7" orient="auto">
              <path d="M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z" fill="#90A0B0"/>
            </marker>
          </defs>

          <!-- RESIDENTS box (top, wide) -->
          <g transform="translate(220, 24)">
            <rect width="440" height="84" fill="#fff" stroke="#90A0B0" stroke-width="1"/>
            <text x="20" y="32" font-family="Source Sans 3, sans-serif" font-size="11" font-weight="700" letter-spacing="1.4" fill="#7AB31F">RESIDENTS &middot; HOMEOWNERS</text>
            <text x="20" y="58" font-family="Geist, sans-serif" font-size="22" font-weight="800" letter-spacing="-0.4" fill="#18335E">The owners of the corporation.</text>
            <text x="20" y="76" font-family="Source Sans 3, sans-serif" font-size="13" fill="#4A5663">Elect the board. Pay assessments. Own the community.</text>
          </g>

          <!-- BOARD box -->
          <g transform="translate(220, 178)">
            <rect width="440" height="92" fill="#18335E" stroke="#18335E"/>
            <text x="20" y="32" font-family="Source Sans 3, sans-serif" font-size="11" font-weight="700" letter-spacing="1.4" fill="#95D031">THE BOARD &middot; ELECTED VOLUNTEERS</text>
            <text x="20" y="60" font-family="Geist, sans-serif" font-size="24" font-weight="900" letter-spacing="-0.5" fill="#ffffff">Governs the HOA corporation.</text>
            <text x="20" y="80" font-family="Source Sans 3, sans-serif" font-size="13" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.78)">Sets policy. Approves budget. Holds fiduciary duty.</text>
          </g>

          <!-- MANAGER box -->
          <g transform="translate(220, 320)">
            <rect width="440" height="92" fill="#fff" stroke="#7AB31F" stroke-width="2"/>
            <text x="20" y="32" font-family="Source Sans 3, sans-serif" font-size="11" font-weight="700" letter-spacing="1.4" fill="#7AB31F">MANAGEMENT COMPANY &middot; THE FIRM YOU HIRE</text>
            <text x="20" y="60" font-family="Geist, sans-serif" font-size="24" font-weight="900" letter-spacing="-0.5" fill="#18335E">Executes the board&rsquo;s direction.</text>
            <text x="20" y="80" font-family="Source Sans 3, sans-serif" font-size="13" fill="#4A5663">Runs the financials, the meetings, the vendors, the requests.</text>
          </g>

          <!-- VENDORS box -->
          <g transform="translate(40, 444)">
            <rect width="340" height="60" fill="#FBFAF6" stroke="#90A0B0" stroke-width="1"/>
            <text x="20" y="26" font-family="Source Sans 3, sans-serif" font-size="11" font-weight="700" letter-spacing="1.4" fill="#7AB31F">VENDORS</text>
            <text x="20" y="48" font-family="Geist, sans-serif" font-size="16" font-weight="700" letter-spacing="-0.2" fill="#18335E">Landscaping, repair, legal, insurance, audit.</text>
          </g>

          <!-- LIVED-IN COMMUNITY box -->
          <g transform="translate(500, 444)">
            <rect width="340" height="60" fill="#FBFAF6" stroke="#90A0B0" stroke-width="1"/>
            <text x="20" y="26" font-family="Source Sans 3, sans-serif" font-size="11" font-weight="700" letter-spacing="1.4" fill="#7AB31F">SERVICE REQUESTS, NOTICES</text>
            <text x="20" y="48" font-family="Geist, sans-serif" font-size="16" font-weight="700" letter-spacing="-0.2" fill="#18335E">Resident-facing communication &amp; ops.</text>
          </g>

          <!-- ARROWS: Residents → Board (elect) -->
          <line x1="320" y1="108" x2="320" y2="170" stroke="#18335E" stroke-width="1.8" marker-end="url(#arrow-navy)"/>
          <text x="332" y="146" font-family="Source Sans 3, sans-serif" font-size="11" font-weight="600" fill="#18335E">elect, fund, own</text>

          <!-- ARROWS: Board ↔ Manager (engages / executes) -->
          <line x1="560" y1="270" x2="560" y2="312" stroke="#7AB31F" stroke-width="1.8" marker-end="url(#arrow-green)"/>
          <text x="572" y="296" font-family="Source Sans 3, sans-serif" font-size="11" font-weight="600" fill="#7AB31F">engages, directs</text>
          <line x1="320" y1="312" x2="320" y2="278" stroke="#90A0B0" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-dasharray="4 3" marker-end="url(#arrow-steel)"/>
          <text x="180" y="296" font-family="Source Sans 3, sans-serif" font-size="11" font-weight="600" fill="#6B7785">reports, recommends</text>

          <!-- ARROWS: Manager → Vendors -->
          <path d="M 320 412 Q 280 420 240 444" stroke="#18335E" stroke-width="1.8" fill="none" marker-end="url(#arrow-navy)"/>
          <text x="160" y="430" font-family="Source Sans 3, sans-serif" font-size="11" font-weight="600" fill="#18335E">contracts, dispatches</text>

          <!-- ARROWS: Manager → Residents (notices) -->
          <path d="M 560 412 Q 600 420 640 444" stroke="#18335E" stroke-width="1.8" fill="none" marker-end="url(#arrow-navy)"/>
          <text x="660" y="430" font-family="Source Sans 3, sans-serif" font-size="11" font-weight="600" fill="#18335E">notices, requests</text>

        </svg>

        <div class="diagram-legend">
          <div class="item" style="--c: #18335E;">
            <span class="swatch">Solid line</span>
            <p>Authority &amp; instruction. The arrow shows who is directing whom.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="item" style="--c: #7AB31F;">
            <span class="swatch">Green line</span>
            <p>The contractual engagement. The board hires the manager; the manager executes.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="item" style="--c: #90A0B0;">
            <span class="swatch">Dashed line</span>
            <p>Reporting upward &mdash; recommendations, financials, status. The manager doesn&rsquo;t decide; the board does.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="item" style="--c: #FBFAF6;">
            <span class="swatch" style="--c: #C9D1DA;">Side boxes</span>
            <p>The two places the manager interfaces with the rest of the world &mdash; vendors and the community.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 02 · WHAT A MANAGER DOES -->
  <section class="sec cream" id="does">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="head">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow"><span class="num">No. 02</span><span class="rule-mini"></span>What a manager does</div>
          <h2>Four categories. <em>One</em> firm.</h2>
        </div>
        <p>The honest one-sentence description: a community management company runs the four functions a board cannot run itself on volunteer time. Where one firm is weak, the board ends up filling the gap unpaid.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="does-grid">

        <article class="does-card">
          <div class="icon"><svg width="28" height="28" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.75" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><line x1="12" y1="2" x2="12" y2="22"/><path d="M17 5H9.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 0 0 7h5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 0 7H6"/></svg></div>
          <div class="body">
            <span class="num">01 &middot; Financial</span>
            <h3>Money &amp; books.</h3>
            <p>The single function that, done well, prevents 80% of the bad outcomes in HOA governance &mdash; and done poorly, causes most of the special assessments.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Collect monthly assessments</li>
              <li>Pay vendors on schedule</li>
              <li>Maintain reserve accounts</li>
              <li>Keep operating &amp; reserve books</li>
              <li>Prepare the annual budget</li>
              <li>Coordinate audit &amp; tax filings</li>
              <li>Bank reconciliations</li>
              <li>Delinquency follow-up</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="does-card">
          <div class="icon"><svg width="28" height="28" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.75" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M3 21h18"/><path d="M5 21V7l8-4v18"/><path d="M19 21V11l-6-4"/><path d="M9 9h.01M9 13h.01M9 17h.01"/></svg></div>
          <div class="body">
            <span class="num">02 &middot; Governance</span>
            <h3>Meetings &amp; records.</h3>
            <p>The unglamorous spine of an HOA &mdash; the part that keeps the board out of trouble with state statute, governing documents, and the eventual challenge.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Prepare board meeting agendas</li>
              <li>Distribute board packets in advance</li>
              <li>Take and file meeting minutes</li>
              <li>Coordinate annual elections</li>
              <li>Maintain governing documents</li>
              <li>Track resolution &amp; rule changes</li>
              <li>Statutory filing &amp; compliance</li>
              <li>Records requests handling</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="does-card">
          <div class="icon"><svg width="28" height="28" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.75" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M14.7 6.3a1 1 0 0 0 0 1.4l1.6 1.6a1 1 0 0 0 1.4 0l3.77-3.77a6 6 0 0 1-7.94 7.94l-6.91 6.91a2.12 2.12 0 0 1-3-3l6.91-6.91a6 6 0 0 1 7.94-7.94l-3.76 3.76z"/></svg></div>
          <div class="body">
            <span class="num">03 &middot; Operations</span>
            <h3>Vendors &amp; the physical asset.</h3>
            <p>The day-to-day running of the community &mdash; the part the board notices when something goes wrong and a vendor is on-site within hours, not days.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Solicit &amp; review vendor bids</li>
              <li>Manage contracts &amp; renewals</li>
              <li>Schedule routine maintenance</li>
              <li>Dispatch emergency repairs</li>
              <li>Inspect common areas</li>
              <li>Coordinate insurance claims</li>
              <li>Reserve study coordination</li>
              <li>Capital project oversight</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="does-card">
          <div class="icon"><svg width="28" height="28" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.75" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M21 15a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H7l-4 4V5a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h14a2 2 0 0 1 2 2z"/></svg></div>
          <div class="body">
            <span class="num">04 &middot; Communications</span>
            <h3>Residents &amp; the board.</h3>
            <p>The flow of information that, when it breaks, generates the bulk of board email at 11 pm. A good manager is the buffer between volunteers and 24-hour resident expectations.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Triage resident requests</li>
              <li>Send statutory notices</li>
              <li>Maintain community portal</li>
              <li>Coordinate ARC submissions</li>
              <li>Process covenant complaints</li>
              <li>Handle move-in / move-out</li>
              <li>Annual disclosure packets</li>
              <li>Newsletter / community updates</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </article>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 03 · WHAT A MANAGER DOESN'T DO -->
  <section class="doesnt-section" id="doesnt">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="head">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow"><span class="num">No. 03</span><span class="rule-mini"></span>What a manager doesn&rsquo;t do</div>
          <h2>What a good firm <em>won&rsquo;t</em> do.</h2>
        </div>
        <p>Half the disputes between boards and management companies are about role confusion &mdash; a board expecting the manager to make calls the board itself has to make. The line is short, and it&rsquo;s here.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="doesnt-grid">
        <article class="doesnt-card">
          <span class="x">&times;</span>
          <h4>Make the board&rsquo;s decisions.</h4>
          <p>The manager can recommend, model, cost, and warn. The decision is the board&rsquo;s. A manager who decides for you has assumed your fiduciary duty without your insurance.</p>
          <span class="footnote">Role &middot; Fiduciary</span>
        </article>
        <article class="doesnt-card">
          <span class="x">&times;</span>
          <h4>Replace the board.</h4>
          <p>The board is elected by the owners. The manager is hired by the board. No volume of service makes a manager into a board member &mdash; and you don&rsquo;t want one who acts like one.</p>
          <span class="footnote">Role &middot; Governance</span>
        </article>
        <article class="doesnt-card">
          <span class="x">&times;</span>
          <h4>Provide legal counsel.</h4>
          <p>The manager flags the issue, identifies counsel from the approved vendor list, and routes the question. The opinion comes from the lawyer, not the firm.</p>
          <span class="footnote">Role &middot; Legal scope</span>
        </article>
        <article class="doesnt-card">
          <span class="x">&times;</span>
          <h4>Set or change rules unilaterally.</h4>
          <p>Rules come from the governing documents and the board&rsquo;s votes. A manager who is &ldquo;creating policy&rdquo; without a board resolution is creating liability.</p>
          <span class="footnote">Role &middot; Authority</span>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 04 · PRICING -->
  <section class="pricing-section" id="pricing">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="head">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow"><span class="num">No. 04</span><span class="rule-mini"></span>What it costs &amp; why</div>
          <h2>Three pricing shapes you&rsquo;ll see <em>in proposals.</em></h2>
        </div>
        <p>HOA management is priced by what&rsquo;s included &mdash; not by what you call it. The three shapes below cover ~95% of proposals you&rsquo;ll receive. <strong>Compare scope, not just sticker price.</strong> The cheapest tier with extras unbundled often costs more in year one than the full-service tier with extras included.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="pricing-grid">
        <div class="col">
          <span class="kind">Tier 01</span>
          <h4>Financial-only</h4>
          <span class="range">$<span class="placeholder placeholder-inline">[8&ndash;14]</span><span class="lbl">per door / month</span></span>
          <p>The cheapest tier. The manager runs the books and the AP/AR, and the board runs everything else. Works for small, self-confident, time-rich boards. Falls apart fast in a transition or a hard year.</p>
          <span class="what-includes">Includes &middot; bookkeeping, AP, AR, reporting</span>
        </div>
        <div class="col feat">
          <span class="kind">Tier 02 &middot; Recommended</span>
          <h4>Full-service</h4>
          <span class="range">$<span class="placeholder placeholder-inline">[18&ndash;28]</span><span class="lbl">per door / month</span></span>
          <p>The category most established HOAs sit in. All four functions above, with a named community manager and a written scope. The 80/20 of value for the price &mdash; and the structure Innovia members are built for.</p>
          <span class="what-includes">Includes &middot; financial, governance, ops, communications</span>
        </div>
        <div class="col">
          <span class="kind">Tier 03</span>
          <h4>On-site / hospitality</h4>
          <span class="range">$<span class="placeholder placeholder-inline">[40&ndash;90]</span><span class="lbl">per door / month</span></span>
          <p>An on-site general manager plus front desk, concierge, and resident services. Common for large condo towers, master-planned communities, and luxury developments. Negotiated by line item.</p>
          <span class="what-includes">Includes &middot; full-service + on-site staffing</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="pricing-footnote">
        <span class="k">Watch&nbsp;for</span>
        <p>Many low-tier proposals exclude transfer fees, ARC reviews, statutory mailings, special meeting attendance, late-fee processing, and reserve study coordination &mdash; each charged per occurrence. Ask for a one-year illustrative invoice with extras priced. <span class="placeholder placeholder-inline">[Rate ranges above are national averages and vary materially by state, association size, and amenity complexity.]</span></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 05 · 8 SIGNS CHECKLIST -->
  <section class="checklist-section" id="signs">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="head">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow"><span class="num">No. 05</span><span class="rule-mini"></span>Eight signs you have the right one</div>
          <h2>What a <em>good</em> management company looks like, in practice.</h2>
        </div>
        <p>Use this as a self-check on your current relationship, or as the rubric for the next proposal you compare. None of these are subjective &mdash; each can be checked against your last 90 days of activity.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="checks">
        <div class="check"><span class="n">01</span><span class="tick"><svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg></span><div class="body"><h4>Financials arrive on a schedule.</h4><p>Monthly statements land by the same date every month. If they slip, you hear about it before you have to ask.</p></div></div>
        <div class="check"><span class="n">02</span><span class="tick"><svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg></span><div class="body"><h4>Board packets are out 5+ days ahead.</h4><p>Agenda, prior minutes, financials, and supporting docs in your inbox before the meeting. Not the morning of.</p></div></div>
        <div class="check"><span class="n">03</span><span class="tick"><svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg></span><div class="body"><h4>The manager flags problems early.</h4><p>You hear about the upcoming budget shortfall or vendor delay weeks ahead, not in the post-mortem.</p></div></div>
        <div class="check"><span class="n">04</span><span class="tick"><svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg></span><div class="body"><h4>Vendor pricing is benchmarked.</h4><p>Each bid comes with at least one comparable, and the manager can explain the trade-off in plain English.</p></div></div>
        <div class="check"><span class="n">05</span><span class="tick"><svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg></span><div class="body"><h4>Reserve health is reviewed annually.</h4><p>The reserve study is updated on the cycle, and a 5-year capital plan exists. Not just a document &mdash; a working tool.</p></div></div>
        <div class="check"><span class="n">06</span><span class="tick"><svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg></span><div class="body"><h4>Resident complaints have a trail.</h4><p>Every request is logged, routed, and closed. The board can see status without making calls.</p></div></div>
        <div class="check"><span class="n">07</span><span class="tick"><svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg></span><div class="body"><h4>The manager defers on policy.</h4><p>The manager identifies the decision and recommends a path &mdash; and the board makes the call. No unilateral rule-making.</p></div></div>
        <div class="check"><span class="n">08</span><span class="tick"><svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg></span><div class="body"><h4>You know who answers the phone.</h4><p>A named community manager. Not a queue, not a ticket. Continuity for at least 18 months running.</p></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 06 · INNOVIA BRIDGE -->
  <section class="bridge">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="head">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow on-dark"><span class="num" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.5)">No. 06</span><span class="rule-mini"></span>Where Innovia members are different</div>
          <h2>Same model. <em>Different</em> back-end.</h2>
        </div>
        <p>Innovia members run the same four functions as every other management company. What changes is what they bring with them: a cooperative-negotiated vendor program, a peer council to escalate hard problems, and a structural alignment that says <strong>this firm owns part of the room your manager comes from.</strong></p>
      </div>

      <div class="three">
        <div class="item">
          <span class="num">01</span>
          <h4>Cooperative vendor program</h4>
          <p>Banking, insurance, reserves, software, and major repair categories are pre-negotiated for the cooperative as a whole. Members pass that pricing into your operating and reserve accounts &mdash; not into the firm&rsquo;s margin.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="item">
          <span class="num">02</span>
          <h4>A peer council behind the firm</h4>
          <p>When your manager hits a hard problem &mdash; a transition, a major capital decision, a litigation question &mdash; they have a council of <span>80+</span> peer firms to consult. Boards don&rsquo;t feel the council directly. They feel the better decision.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="item">
          <span class="num">03</span>
          <h4>Member-owned, no roll-up</h4>
          <p>The cooperative is owned by its operator members. There&rsquo;s no private equity acquirer to pay back, no national brand to feed margin to. The structure is built to keep firms independent &mdash; and therefore aligned with your board.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="find">
        <div class="lhs">
          <span class="dot"></span>
          <p>Find an Innovia member serving your county.</p>
        </div>
        <a href="/find-a-management-company/#inquiry">Open the directory <svg class="arrow" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.4" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M5 12h14"/><path d="m13 6 6 6-6 6"/></svg></a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 07 · CTA -->
  <section class="cta-finale">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="frame">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--innovia-navy); opacity: 0.65;"><span class="num" style="color: var(--innovia-navy);">No. 07</span><span class="rule-mini"></span>Next step</div>
          <h2>Ready to compare <em>real proposals?</em></h2>
          <p class="lead">Tell us about your community in five minutes. We&rsquo;ll route the inquiry to the Innovia-backed firm best positioned to serve your county and property type. One match. No call lists. No spam.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="actions">
          <a href="/find-a-management-company/#inquiry" class="btn btn-navy">
            Send a board inquiry
            <svg class="arrow" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M5 12h14"/><path d="m13 6 6 6-6 6"/></svg>
          </a>
          <a href="/board-education/" class="btn btn-outline">More board education</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FOOTER -->
  


  
